The William James College INTERFACE Referral Service, offered through the Freedman Center, is an outpatient mental health and wellness referral helpline available Monday through Friday, 9 am-5 pm, at 888-244-6843 (toll free).

This is a free, confidential referral service for residents and public school students of participating communities (including Wakefield). Callers from these participating communities are matched with licensed outpatient mental health providers from our extensive database, on average, within 2 weeks of their call to INTERFACE.

Each referral best meets the specialty needs, insurance or fee requirement, location and availability needs of the caller.

For more information please visit:
The Interface Facebook Page: facebook.com/INTERFACEReferralService
or their website: interface.williamjames.edu

shared_text:
Wakefield Memorial High School
July 8 at 12:35 PM ·

We are sorry to inform you that the Senior Prom, scheduled at Danversport for August 3, has been cancelled. Based on the updated State guidance for phase 3, Danversport has confirmed that they will only be able to offer a meal to 100 guests maximum with no dancing. These are not the conditions that will allow for a celebratory and fun senior prom.

However, the Senior Committee is currently working with the Class Advisors, the Class Officers, and administration to put together an alternative celebration for early August which will include viewing footage from graduation and the senior show combined with food and some activities that can be done with appropriate social-distancing and masks. We are still looking into possibilities for this event and more information will be out as soon as possible.

More to come.

post_id:
Our PreK-12 summer reading program information is now available on the Wakefield Reads website: wakefieldreads.org.
This website features a program overview and suggested summer reading lists.

All students PK-12 are challenged to read four books over the summer. As a special piece of this challenge, students are encouraged to read at least one STEAM (science, technology, engineering, art, math) non-fiction title.

We are grateful for our partnership with the Lucius Beebe Memorial Library. The always incredible Beebe Library staff works in conjunction with our district librarians to create suggested reading lists and engaging programming throughout the summer.

Additionally, the Beebe Library continues to provide access to free reading materials and digital media. Please visit this site to access their digital subscription services: https://www.wakefieldlibrary.org/databases/

image:
Town of Wakefield, MA - Government
June 5 at 10:00 AM ·

This afternoon, the Wakefield Memorial High School Class of 2020 will celebrate with a car parade. If you’re along the parade route, please be sure to give them a wave! They are scheduled to depart the High School at 3:30 p.m.

Please make a note of their route for traffic purposes:
Seniors will cruise down Old Nahant, to Oak, to Greenwood Ave. The parade will take a right onto Pitman and head North on Main for a drive past the Galvin Middle School. The parade will take a right onto Lowell and continue onto Vernon. Seniors will take a left on Water, a right on Farm and conclude back at the high school.

Congratulations to the Class of 2020!

Wakefield Families,

Today, we write to let everyone know that we share the pain, anger, and grief regarding the senseless killing of George Floyd, and other acts of violence against communities of color, particularly Black men. The outrage that has gripped this nation is fueled by decades and decades of racism, hatred, and injustices that should never be tolerated. As educational leaders, we denounce all forms of racism and hatred and stand in solidarity with those protesting this unconscionable death, and the many that came before it.

The Wakefield Public Schools and the community we serve are determined to create meaningful and lasting positive change that addresses systemic racism.…

Repost from WEF Wakefield Educational Foundation:

“WEF Virtual Celebration of Learning:

The Wakefield Educational Foundation has been celebrating individuals who make a difference in our schools and community since the inception of the Celebration of Learning Ceremony in 1996.
2020 marks WEF’s 24th year of recognizing exceptional leadership and engagement by students, staff and volunteers. While WEF had to cancel this year’s award ceremony,we decided to move forward with recognition of our exemplary students and, with the collaboration of building principals, created a virtual recognition of this year’s student recipients. You can view the finished virtual recognition here:

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1e8zuGThtSI4TVLAw6rpIYRb9BVMcbdaE/view?usp=sharing

We hope you enjoy!!”

WEF Wakefield Educational Foundation
April 20 at 6:53 PM ·

In early March, Neal Nichols hosted his Geography Gameshow for 6th grade students at the Galvin Middle School. The program provided some friendly competition among classmates as a way to reinforce their social studies curriculum. Nichols, an artist and seasoned international traveler, rendered a large map from memory, as he engaged students in a series of discussions and trivia contests about Ancient Civilizations.

The Geography Gameshow was sponsored by The Galvin School PTO and a grant from the Wakefield Educational Foundation (WEF).

WEF has awarded over $380,000 to schools across the Wakefield Public Schools district since 1989. Learn more by following WEF on Twitter or Facebook, or go to www.WEF01880.org.

post_text:
Wakefield High School Bands
April 9 at 11:00 AM ·

For the 8th time in 9 years, the NAMM Foundation has named the Wakefield Public School District one of the "Best Communities for Music Education." in the country.
Districts were chosen for this honor because they demonstrate outstanding achievement in their efforts to provide music access and education to all students. This year, 754 school districts from across the country and 15 school districts in Massachusetts received this honor.
The “Best Communities” designation recognizes collaborative, from-the-ground-up efforts for teachers, administrators, students and parents who continually work to keep comprehensive music education as an integral part of the core curriculum. These districts also lead the way with learning opportunities as outlined in the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA), which recommends music and the arts as important elements of a well-rounded education for all children.

Each day of the month April the WMHS faculty and staff will share or recite a poem in honor of National Poetry Month. Today would have been the home opener at Fenway Park- and so we present to you the timeless baseball poem “Casey at the Bat” by EL Travers, performed by WMHS faculty member Ms. ME Macri (math department).

To see all of the poetry presented this month, please follow or like the WMHS Gov. John A. Volpe Library page.

"Casey at the Bat" by EL Thayer - Read by Ms. ME Macri

WMHS Gov. John A. Volpe Library
April 2 at 7:00 AM ·

Today's poem is "Casey at the Bat" written by Ernest Lawrence Thayer and performed here by Ms. ME Macri.

Today would have been the Red Sox home opener. We hope this long-loved poem about baseball touches your hearts and gets you geared up for hundreds of nailbiter baseball games to come.

As a reminder, we'll be sharing out a new poem each day in April as part of a celebration for National Poetry Month. We hope you enjoy.

shared_text:
Brendan Kent
March 20 at 5:21 PM ·

This week has been a difficult week for lots of people around the world, but if there is ever anything that cheers me up, it is hearing about the great accomplishments of our students. And so amidst all of the negative news this week, I am happy to announce some positive news. I hope this helps lift everyone's spirits a bit heading into this weekend.

I am happy to announce that two of our Wakefield HS student-athletes were selected to the prestigious Boston Herald All-Scholastic team this week. Whale Day at the Walton!!

Walton students enjoyed “Whale Day” with a visit from the New England Aquarium thanks to a grant from Wakefield Educational Foundation (WEF). The grant allowed students in grades 1-4 to learn about whales through a series of interactive exhibits alongside a giant inflatable right whale named “Calvin”. Kindergarten students also benefited from the grant with the Aquarium’s Tidepools Alive hands-on program.

WEF has awarded over $380,000 to schools across the Wakefield Public Schools district since 1989. Learn more by following WEF on Twitter or Facebook, or go to www.WEF01880.org.

(Photo Credit: Stephanie Goryl)
